			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64613073">		
		on Tuesday July 09, 2024 @01:18PM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23382245&amp;cid=64613073">#64613073</a>)
		<small><a href="//slashdot.org/~Shakrai/journal/" title="Friday September 24, 2010 @11:15AM" class="user_journal_display">Journal</a> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64613073"><p><div class="quote"><p>It would be nice if I could exceed the speed limit to get my kid to the hospital in an emergency, if conditions allowed it.</p></div><p>I made the same argument in the US with our mandate for drunk driving detection technology.  Besides the fact that there is no proven technology that doesn't give significant numbers of false-positives (ask a diabetic), even a 0.001% false positive rate (likely unattainable with current tech) means 11,000 <b> <i>daily</i> </b> denied trips (1.1 billion trips each day, <a href="https://www.bts.gov/statistical-products/surveys/national-household-travel-survey-daily-travel-quick-facts" title="bts.gov">source</a> [bts.gov]), there are rare occasions where the defense of <a href="https://www.law.cornell.edu/wex/justification" title="cornell.edu">justification</a> [cornell.edu] would come into play vis-a-vis drunk driving.  I'll give you one, living in wildfire country, you might get a Level 3 Go Now evacuation order with next to no notice.  Two to three drinks are sufficient to put someone on the wrong side of 0.08, so, I guess if I've indulged in three beers on a random Sunday afternoon I have to burn to death?  My car is going to refuse to let me flee the danger zone?  No cop would cite you for drunk driving while fleeing a wildfire and if they did no court would convict you, but that won't matter, your car will simply refuse to drive.
</p><p>The false positives are an even bigger problem and I can't wait for the lawsuits when someone is denied a trip to the hospital, resulting in a fatality, because the system wrongly thought they were drunk, or accurately detected it but denied a trip wherein the defense of justification would have been legitimate.
</p><p>Oh, and of course, the added expense to the vehicle purchase for 100% of the population when less than 1% engages in drunk driving.  That's fun too.  Thanks Nanny State.
</p><p>Random musing: A few months ago, I ran a red light because there was an ambulance behind with me with lights and sirens, stuck in traffic with no way to get around it.  The technology already exists to prevent cars from running red lights.  Is that coming next?  This particular intersection has a traffic camera and I got flashed.  Never got a ticket, because a human being in the local police department has to review the footage before one is issued, and I assume that person applied the crazy concept of COMMON SENSE when they saw the full circumstance.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64613073">
<span class="ind"></span><a id="reply_link_64613073" class="btn link" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23382245&amp;op=Reply&amp;threshold=1&amp;commentsort=0&amp;mode=thread&amp;pid=64613073" onclick="D2.replyTo(64613073); return false;">Reply to This</a> <span class="ind"></span><a class="btn link" href="//tech.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23382245&amp;threshold=1&amp;commentsort=0&amp;mode=thread&amp;cid=64612875" onclick="return D2.selectParent(64612875)">Parent</a> 	<a href="#" class="comment_share_toggle btn link">Share</a>
